  "prompt": "Which enzyme uses both NAD+ and NADP+ as a coenzyme?",
  "response": "One enzyme that can use both NAD\u207a and NADP\u207a as coenzymes is **glutamate dehydrogenase (GDH)**. This enzyme plays a key role in amino acid metabolism, catalyzing the reversible oxidative deamination of glutamate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate and ammonia, while reducing NAD\u207a or NADP\u207a to NADH or NADPH, respectively.\n\nGDH is unique in its ability to utilize either NAD\u207a (typically associated with catabolic processes) or NADP\u207a (often linked to biosynthetic pathways), allowing it to function in both energy production and biosynthesis of amino acids. However, its affinity for NAD\u207a and NADP\u207a may vary depending on the organism or isoform of the enzyme.",
